ull, "body": "I am maintaining a AUR package (https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/python-cursor/) for `cursor` since August 2018. If you think that this is done right (the package build instructions can be seen in the PKGBUILD https://aur.archlinux.org/cgit/aur.git/tree/PKGBUILD?h=python-cursor), we could mention this as the preferred way to install `cursor` for Arch Linux users. Maybe we could write somehing like this in the README:\r\n\r\n**Arch Linux:**\r\nThe package is available in the [AUR](https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/python-cursor/). You can either use a AUR helper or manually install it:\r\n```\r\ngit clone https://aur.archlinux.org/python-cursor.git\r\ncd python-cursor\r\nmakepkg -si\r\nsudo pacman -U python-cursor-x.y.z-r-any.pkg.xz\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn addition, many people do not consider it as _good practice_ to use `sudo pip` to install python packages. It installs the python files on your system path, which is usually already maintained by the system's package manager (`pacman` for Arch users, `apt-get` for Debian/Ubuntu users). Maybe you should encourage users to set up virtual environments or at least use `pip install ---user` to install the package.", "performed_via_github_app": null, "score": 1.0}, {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/GijsTimmers/cursor/issues/4", "repository_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/GijsTimmers/cursor", "labels_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/GijsTimmers/cursor/issues/4/labels{/name}", "comments_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/GijsTimmers/cursor/issues/4/comments", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/GijsTimmers/cursor/issues/4/events", "html_url": "https://github.com/GijsTimmers/cursor/issues/4", "id": 401794972, "node_id": "MDU6SXNzdWU0MDE3OTQ5NzI=", "number": 4, "title": "license issue", "user": {"login": "PatrikKopkan", "id": 24222200, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjI0MjIyMjAw", "avatar_url": "https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/24222200?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/P